post_text:
A note from the Moffat County School District Nurse:

For clarification, the Abbott ID Now testing machine purchased is to be used by Moffat County Public Health for the benefit of the Community.
Moffat County School District is collaborating with MCPH to have the ability to rapid test "SYMPTOMATIC" staff and students within the district, to help decrease the amount of people that are required to quarantine while waiting for a test result.
The Moffat County School health team, will collaborate with Moffat County Public Health and parents before a test is completed. All tests will have to be parent authorized prior to the test happening. This test will be at no cost to the parent/staff and or student.
This is an amazing breakthrough to help support parents that have chosen face to face/ in person learning. If parents have any further questions, please feel free to reach out to Moffat County Public Health or Myranda Lyons, Moffat County School District Nurse.

Employee Spotlight: Terri Robinson

Terri is the preschool secretary and the first face that you will see as you enter the Early Childhood Center. Terri has been part of the preschool program for five years and during this time has made many positive connections with preschoolers, their families, and staff members. Terri always has a smile on her face and greets everyone with enthusiasm and her love for young children. She has four young grandchildren of her own that she loves dearly, and hundreds of “adopted” young children that she has loved and nurtured during their time in preschool.

post_text:
Employee Spotlight: Cassia McDiffett!

Cassia McDiffett has worked for Moffat County School district for 24 years. She is currently a high school math teacher, but for a period of time also served as the district's Math Coordinator helping all elementary schools implement a new math curriculum and practices.

She loves seeing former students grow up, accomplish their dreams, seeing them with their family and being successful. "That is what public education is all about!" She also speaks positively of the times when she worked side-by-side coaching teachers when she was the math coordinator.

She remembers when she started teaching and there were no computers or even telephones in the classrooms, and notes that things have changed a lot during her career. But her goal always remains the same: Teaching students to think!

When not teaching, Cassia enjoys time with her family and participating with their activities. She also enjoys quilting and the outdoors, but only when the weather is nice.

post_text:
Keeping in positive!

Ridgeview Elementary School is so proud of our Vex IQ robotics teams! Even though the season ended abruptly with the pandemic, the Triple Threat team qualified for the World’s Vex IQ tournament. Instead of traveling to Kentucky, the event was virtual. The teams gathered virtually with a Zoom watch party, and watched the virtual fantasy event! Team members are excited about next year’s competition, which was revealed at the end of the World’s event.
Congratulations to Curtis Kuberry, Yahir Duarte, Kainen Verberg and Indy Mayer, as well as coaches Jennifer Stagner, Rhonda Counts and Ty Kuberry!

Employee Spotlight: Shannon Mose!

Shannon has worked for the MCSD District as the Transportation and Maintenance departments secretary. Over the course of her time here she has helped to develop and implement several streamlined processes in both departments. She brings numerous years of experience to the table and is always willing to jump in with both feet!
Shannon will be retiring on May 20th of this year and moving back to Michigan to spend more time with her family and grandkids. To say, “She has been a great asset for both departments” would be an understatement and she will be missed.

𝗠𝗖𝗦𝗗 𝗜𝗦 𝗡𝗢𝗧 collecting or requesting any money for insurance for your student's iPad. Any questions about this contact SRO Nathan Businger or MCSD directly.

post_text:
Our Employee Spotlight this week is Alicia Townsend!
Alicia Townsend has worked in this district for 28 years - "I'm going to try and stay away from all the cliches about it just seeming like yesterday that I started. I think when you are in the trenches and the day has been tough it's hard to remember where we have come from. I have seen growth in many areas in our district over the years. I've seen us falter a few steps as well. What has always made this job worth doing is the people; both the people that I work with and the kids that we serve and their families. It's sometimes hard to remember that struggles and frustrations are how we grow. I have been pushed, challenged, and taught many things by both professionals and the kids that I work with on a daily basis. I am grateful for this community, it's people and the opportunity to work here everyday.

post_text:
Check out our Employee Spotlight of the week, Vera Turner.
Our Gifted Education Coordinator is a gift to Northwest Colorado - Vera Turner has served our district in multiple capacities over her 17 years of employment. She has been a Special Education Teacher, Response to Intervention Coordinator, and Literacy Coordinator. She currently serves the district and Northwest BOCES as our regional Gifted Education Director where her passion for gifted education and identifying underserved populations has benefited many. In addition, she is MCSD's District Assessment Coordinator. Vera possesses the rare ability to see all of the details while also being able to see the big picture which is crucial in overseeing the many strict rules that govern state testing. What we love most about interacting with Vera is her sense of humor. Witty and dry - she keeps us all on our toes...

Our employee featured in this week's Employee Spotlight is Lorrae Moon.
Since the fall of 1992, Lorrae Moon has been transporting our students not only on their way to and from school but she has also driven hundreds of our athletes over the years to their events. School bus drivers are often the first and last connection to school that students experience each day and Lorrae takes that connection very seriously. Lorrae is waiting at the bus stop bright and early with her good morning greetings and wishes for great days at school. She is a great role model for her riders and her connections to our community reach much further than her role as a bus driver. We are proud Lorrae continues to choose MCSD and our kids.

Our Employee Spotlight this week is Maria Morales with Food Service.
If you have worked or visited East Elementary or Sunset Elementary you would have seen Maria Morales smiling face. She has worked for the school district for 8 years now and has been in Craig for almost 25 years. Maria enjoys working with her co-workers and students at each school.

Maria's pride that she takes in her work is truly inspiring. Her efforts at strengthening the lunchroom culture do not go unnoticed by the way she remembers student's names and what condiments they would like.
Having Maria on the Food Service Team make a huge difference. Keep up the great work!
text:
Our Employee Spotlight this week is Maria Morales with Food Service.
If you have worked or visited East Elementary or Sunset Elementary you would have seen Maria Morales smiling face. She has worked for the school district for 8 years now and has been in Craig for almost 25 years. Maria enjoys working with her co-workers and students at each school.

Maria's pride that she takes in her work is truly inspiring. Her efforts at strengthening the lunchroom culture do not go unnoticed by the way she remembers student's names and what condiments they would like.
Having Maria on the Food Service Team make a huge difference. Keep up the great work!

post_text:
A MESSAGE FROM THE MOFFAT COUNTY SCHOOL DISTRICT BOARD OF EDUCATION
As Dr. Ulrich has shared with the Board of Education, he will leave the Moffat County School District (MCSD) at the end of this school year, returning to Missouri to serve as the superintendent of the Kirkwood School District. It is with the warmest wishes that we thank him for his service to our community and his leadership in our district. Dr. Ulrich will continue in his role with the full confidence of the board through June 2020.

A superintendent search will begin immediately. Our goal is to name a new leader by the end of the school year with a start date of July 1, 2020.

In MCSD, we are focused on living our mission to educate and inspire students to succeed in an environment of change. In our search, we will be seeking a leader who will ensure that we continue on a positive path, guided by our strategic plan, toward providing exceptional academic programming and facilities for our students.

post_text:
Our Employee Spotlight for this week is Joy Tegtman. Thank you for all you do.

Joy has worked for MCHS for 19 years as an Alternative Education teacher as well as a Social Studies teacher. She recalls many memorable moments spread out over those years. However, what has been most inspiring and has kept her enthusiasm about teaching, is when students succeed. She has witnessed many successes, even from students who have had tremendous odds stacked against them. When not at school, she enjoys spending time with her grown children, walking and playing with her three dogs and reading. She considers herself a life-long learner.

shared_text:
CMS Activities & Athletics
February 7 at 9:30 AM ·

Dear Parents,
Due to weather conditions, specifically over Rabbit Ears Pass, the athletic directors in our league have reorganized the Middle School Girls District Basketball Tournament. Rangely will now be hosting A-D teams that are able to make it. With this change he is reworking the brackets and will have those ready by this afternoon. We have and will continue to be in close contact with all local authorities regarding road conditions throughout the day and into the morning to make sure the travel to Rangely is a safe choice.
As soon as the brackets are done I will have them sent out via email to families.

At least one of the Craig Middle School teams will play at 9am tomorrow.
We will leave from CMS at 5:30am.

I appreciate your support and patience through these changes and ask that we thank the Rangely Schools for coming together to make this happen for our kids.

Bring your dollars to vote for your favorite Top 20 Artists or bid on one of our silent auction items. All proceeds go to Connections 4 Kids and assist us in delivering resources and quality early childhood experiences for our young families. See you soon!
